snippet: A see-saw session on Wall Street on Monday ended little changed, with gains in big bank stocks offsetting a drag from Apple, as investors braced for the Federal Reserve meeting later this week.

headline.main: Wall Street Ends Flat as Banks Gain, Apple Drags

snippet: General Electric is digging deeper into biotechnology with plans to build four prefabricated drug factories in Ireland, bringing to Europe a low-cost manufacturing concept it first pioneered in China.

headline.main: GE Brings Off-The-Shelf Biotech Drug Factories to Ireland
headline.print_headline: GE Brings Off-The-Shelf Biotech Drug Factories to Ireland

snippet: European Union antitrust regulators opened a probe on Monday into tax deals granted by Luxembourg to French power utility Engie, stepping up the EU's campaign against tax avoidance by multinationals.

headline.main: EU Opens Probe Into Tax Deals Between Luxembourg and Engie
headline.print_headline: EU Opens Probe Into Tax Deals Between Luxembourg and Engie

snippet: As G.E., Oracle, Salesforce.com and others push their A.I. products, it remains unclear whether potential customers understand how they will profit.
abstract: Sales and marketing company Salesforce.com introduces Einstein, artificial intelligence system that examines client's customer data to determine marketing leads and suggest new products; firm joins growing boom in AI services that provide insights and predict future behavior from information captured via web.

headline.main: Artificial Intelligence Software Is Booming. But Why Now?
headline.print_headline: Why Artificial Intelligence Software Is Booming

snippet: Restaurants in Palo Alto are increasingly struggling as rents soar and workers are hired away by the corporate cafeterias of behemoths like Google.
abstract: Restaurateurs in Palo Alto, Calif, and other parts of Silicon Valley say tech bubble is disrupting food service industry and forcing many establishments to scale down or bust as result of rising rents, high local fees and acute labor shortages.
